üó≥Ô∏è Cost of Living & Marginal Seats in Victoria: A Data-Driven Political Insight

A personal project exploring the intersection of federal election results, housing costs, and census data in Victoria, Australia.

Created by HARDIK AJAY DIXIT | Data Analyst & R Enthusiast

2025-03-25

üîç Project Overview

This project is a personal exploration of how cost of living indicators (like rent and mortgage payments) intersect with marginal seats from the 2022 Australian Federal Election, focusing on Victoria.

I was curious: Are voters in marginal electorates more vulnerable to financial stress? To investigate this, I combined election result data with census data from 2016 and 2021, visualizing key metrics geographically using R.

1 üß© Identifying Marginal Seats in Victoria

1.1 Load and filter election results to find marginal seats won with <56% of preference votes.

election_data <- read.csv("data/HouseDopByDivisionDownload-27966.csv", skip = 1)

  
# Filter to only include seats in Victoria
Marginal_seats <- election_data %>%
  filter(StateAb == "VIC") %>% 
  
# Filter to only Preference Count
  filter(CalculationType == "Preference Percent" & Elected == "Y") %>%
      group_by(DivisionNm) %>%  
  
# Filter Marginal winning seats less than 56%
  filter(CountNumber == max(CountNumber))
Marginal_seats <- Marginal_seats %>% select(StateAb,DivisionNm,CountNumber,Surname,GivenNm,PartyNm, PartyAb,CalculationType, CalculationValue) %>%
  mutate(marginal = ifelse(CalculationValue < 56 , "Y" , "N")) %>% filter(marginal == "Y") %>%
  mutate(DivisionNm=toupper(DivisionNm))%>% arrange(DivisionNm)

2.3.1 üîé Limitations of Using 30% Rule as Stress Indicator

Lack of precision: Using the average housing cost and 30% of the average household income as proxy for mortgage/rental stress can only give a ballpark figure. Individual circumstances, such as the number of dependents, work status, and other elements that influence household income and expenses are not taken into consideration.

Regional variations: Housing expenses can vary widely from one place to another. Victoria‚Äôs diverse housing markets might not be adequately represented by a single criterion applied to the entire state.

Data gaps: The census does not fully account for costs associated with dwelling, such as utilities, property taxes, and maintenance costs.As such, comparing the median amount of money spent on housing to 30% of the median household income may not give a complete picture of the financial stress faced by households.

Changes over time: Due to changes in the housing market and the wider economy over time, comparing the median amount spent on housing in 2016 and 2021 and the 30% criterion may not be appropriate. For instance, changes in interest rates, rental costs, and household earnings over time may all have an impact on the percentage of households that are stressed out about their mortgage or rent.

3 üìçMapping Cost of Living Stress by Electorate (Personal Spatial Analysis)

In this section, I explored how spatial divisions (SA1 regions) align with federal electorates in Victoria. My main goal was to visualise and compare cost of living indicators between marginal and non-marginal seats using Census 2021 data.

3.1 üß≠ Mapping SA1s to Divisions

joined_map_2016 <- st_join(st_centroid(census_2016), vic_map) %>%
  st_join(census_2016 %>% select(sa1_7digitcode_2016), .)

ggplot(data = joined_map_2016) +
   geom_sf(aes(geometry = geom, fill = DivisionNm)) +
  geom_sf(data = vic_map,
          aes(geometry = geometry), col = "red", fill = "transparent")

joined_map_2021 <- st_join(st_centroid(census_2021), vic_map) %>%
  st_join(census_2021 %>% select(SA1_CODE_2021), .)

ggplot(data = joined_map_2021) +
   geom_sf(aes(geometry = geom, fill = DivisionNm)) +
  geom_sf(data = vic_map,
          aes(geometry = geometry), col = "red", fill = "transparent")

SA1_Melb_2016 <- joined_map_2016 %>%
  filter(DivisionNm == "MELBOURNE")

SA1_Melb_2021 <- joined_map_2021 %>%
  filter(DivisionNm == "MELBOURNE")

The number of SA1 Regions in Melbourne in 2016 are 339 and in 2021 are 461.

3.2 üìä Calculating Average Cost Indicators for Melbourne

Mean_Melb <- SA1_Melb_2021%>%
  summarise(Mean_mortgage_repay_monthly_2021 = mean(Median_mortgage_repay_monthly),
            Mean_rent_weekly_2021 = mean(Median_rent_weekly),
            Mean_tot_hhd_inc_weekly_2021 = mean(Median_tot_hhd_inc_weekly))

üìå Process Recap:

  • Loaded both 2016 and 2021 GeoPackage datasets.
  • Filtered Victoria‚Äôs data to focus on Melbourne‚Äôs SA1s.
  • Calculated the mean for mortgage, rent, and household income indicators across these areas.

‚ö†Ô∏è Note: These means are derived from median values per SA1, not raw income or housing payments. As such, it‚Äôs an approximation for high-level comparison only.

3.3 üìç Visualising Cost of Living in Marginal vs Non-Marginal

  Electorates

I calculated cost of living ratios ‚Äî rent/income and mortgage/income ‚Äî across marginal and non-marginal electorates to explore spatial inequalities.

marginal_joined_map_2021 <- joined_map_2021 %>%
  filter(DivisionNm %in% c("ASTON", "CASEY", "DEAKIN", "GOLDSTEIN", "HIGGINS", "KOOYONG", "MCEWEN", "MENZIES", "MONASH", "NICHOLLS", "WANNON"))

costofliving_marginial <- marginal_joined_map_2021 %>%
  mutate(col_rent = (Median_rent_weekly/Median_tot_hhd_inc_weekly),
         col_mortgage = (Median_mortgage_repay_monthly/Median_tot_hhd_inc_weekly))

3.4 Rent Stress: Marginal Seats

col_rent_map <- costofliving_marginial %>%
   mutate(centroid = st_centroid(geom)) %>%
   filter(Median_age_persons != 0)

ggplot(col_rent_map) +
   geom_sf(aes(geometry = centroid, color = col_rent), shape = 3) +
   geom_sf(data = vic_map, aes(geometry = geometry), fill = "transparent", size = 1.3, color = "black") +
   coord_sf(xlim = c(144.8, 145.2), ylim = c(-38.1, -37.6)) +
   scale_color_viridis_c(name = "Rent For Marginal Seats", option = "magma")

nonmarginal_joined_map_2021 <- joined_map_2021 %>%
  filter(!(DivisionNm %in% c("ASTON", "CASEY", "DEAKIN", "GOLDSTEIN", "HIGGINS", "KOOYONG", "MCEWEN", "MENZIES", "MONASH", "NICHOLLS", "WANNON")))

costofliving_nonmarginial <- nonmarginal_joined_map_2021 %>%
  mutate(col_rent = (Median_rent_weekly/Median_tot_hhd_inc_weekly),
         col_mortgage = (Median_mortgage_repay_monthly/Median_tot_hhd_inc_weekly))

3.5 Rent Stress: Non-Marginal Seats

col_rent_map_non <- costofliving_nonmarginial %>%

ggplot(col_rent_map_non) +

4 üßæ Key Findings & Reflections

  • Our analysis of the 2021 Census data suggests that voters in marginal seats are facing a greater impact from the cost of living crisis than those in other electorates. We estimated the median amount of money spent on housing (mortgage/rent). We found that a higher percentage of voters in marginal seats were in mortgage or rental stress compared to other electorates.

  • Additionally, we estimated the mean of several economic variables for each electorate, including Median_mortgage_repay_monthly, Median_rent_weekly, and Median_tot_hhd_inc_weekly. We found that in marginal seats, the median values for Median_mortgage_repay_monthly and Median_rent_weekly were higher than the median values for other electorates. The median value for Median_tot_hhd_inc_weekly in marginal seats was lower than that of other electorates.

  • However, it is important to note that the census data has limitations, particularly when it comes to small sample sizes in some electorates. Therefore, the results may not be entirely representative of the entire electorate. Additionally, these findings do not account for other factors that may contribute to the cost of living, such as transport or energy costs.

  • In conclusion, our analysis suggests that voters in marginal seats are being impacted more by the cost of living crisis than voters in other electorates. We recommend that the Labor Party take into account these findings when developing policies aimed at addressing the cost of living crisis.
